{
  
  if(isTRUE(i > 1) || is.null(i))

    print(i)

We can say that it is not obvious to resample data, we can make predictions for one day and it will be quite accurate and full. If we will take for day or month we can lose some info that will be critical for people’ life. Also there is no such big outliers that require smoothing

Stationarity

We should understand the character of the data to analyze correctly and may be we can use easier methods. So we need to check. We must determine if the data was generated by a stationary process, and possibly to transform it so it has the properties of a sample generated by such a process. In ARIMA data must be stationar.

For test we will use Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test

adf.test(df$Rainfall,alternative="stationary")
## Warning in adf.test(df$Rainfall, alternative = "stationary"): p-value smaller
## than printed p-value
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  df$Rainfall
## Dickey-Fuller = -14.579, Lag order = 16, p-value = 0.01
## alternative hypothesis: stationary
clean_df <- na.omit(df)
adf.test(clean_df$Depth_to_Groundwater, alternative = "stationary")
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  clean_df$Depth_to_Groundwater
## Dickey-Fuller = -1.8431, Lag order = 15, p-value = 0.6448
## alternative hypothesis: stationary
adf.test(clean_df$Temperature, alternative = "stationary")
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  clean_df$Temperature
## Dickey-Fuller = -3.5295, Lag order = 15, p-value = 0.03943
## alternative hypothesis: stationary
adf.test(clean_df$` Volume`, alternative = "stationary")
## Warning in adf.test(clean_df$` Volume`, alternative = "stationary"): p-value
## smaller than printed p-value
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  clean_df$` Volume`
## Dickey-Fuller = -5.7894, Lag order = 15, p-value = 0.01
## alternative hypothesis: stationary
adf.test(clean_df$` Hydrometry`, alternative = "stationary")
## Warning in adf.test(clean_df$` Hydrometry`, alternative = "stationary"): p-value
## smaller than printed p-value
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  clean_df$` Hydrometry`
## Dickey-Fuller = -5.5771, Lag order = 15, p-value = 0.01
## alternative hypothesis: stationary

If p - value is less then 0.05 it means that stationary data else non - stationary and we need to do some actions with data. In our case only depth has non - stationary distribution.

depth <- na_interpolation(df$Depth_to_Groundwater, option = "linear")
depth <- log10(abs(depth))
adf.test(depth, alternative = "stationary")
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  depth
## Dickey-Fuller = -1.704, Lag order = 16, p-value = 0.7037
## alternative hypothesis: stationary

We see that p-value=0.6814 > 0.05. It means that data is not stationary and we need to use other way.

#depth <- df$Depth_to_Groundwater
depth <- diff(depth) # make it stationary
#depth <- df$Depth_to_Groundwater - shift(df$Depth_to_Groundwater, n=1, type = 'shift')
depth <- na_interpolation(depth, option = "linear")
adf.test(depth, alternative = "stationary")
## Warning in adf.test(depth, alternative = "stationary"): p-value smaller than
## printed p-value
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  depth
## Dickey-Fuller = -12.882, Lag order = 16, p-value = 0.01
## alternative hypothesis: stationary

As we can see p-value is less than 0.05 that means that we got stationary data Get trend, seasonal and noise. Compare with reality

depth_ts <- ts(depth, start = df$Date[1], frequency=365)
depth_ts <- diff(depth_ts)
decomposed_ts <- decompose(depth_ts, type=c("additive"))
plot( df$Depth_to_Groundwater, ylab = "Real", main="Real", axes=FALSE, type="l")+geom_line()

## NULL
plot( decomposed_ts$seasonal, ylab = "Seasonal", main="Seasonal", axes=FALSE, type="l")

plot( decomposed_ts$trend, ylab = "Trend", main="Depth", axes=FALSE, type="l")

plot( decomposed_ts$random, ylab = "Random", main="Random", axes=FALSE, type="l")

As we can see wa have stationary data

Analyse data

the most convinient and normal is to analyse seasonal

depth_ts <- ts(depth, start = df$Date[1], frequency=365)
depth_ts <- na_interpolation(depth_ts, option = "linear")
decomposed_ts <- decompose(depth_ts, type=c("additive"))
plot( decomposed_ts$seasonal, xlab="Time", ylab = "Seasonal", main="Depth", axes=FALSE, type="l")
box()

df$Temperature <- na_interpolation(df$Temperature, option = "linear")
temperature_ts <- ts(df$Temperature, start = df$Date[1], frequency=365)
decomposed_ts <- decompose(temperature_ts, type=c("additive"))
plot( decomposed_ts$seasonal, xlab="Time", ylab = "Seasonal", main="Temperature", axes=FALSE, type="l")
box()

plot(depth, type='l', main="Depth")

We see that there is no increasing or decreasing for a long time intervals, that means that we got stationary data.

Arima model

We have stationary data so we can use ARIMA model.

plot( depth,xlab = "Time", ylab = "Depth", main="Depth", axes=FALSE, type="l")
axis(1,at=seq(df$Date[1], df$Date[length(df$Date)], by="years"),labels=unique(as.character(df$Date, format= "%Y")))

We will build ACF, PACF functions.

depth_ts <- ts(depth, start = df$Date[1], frequency=1)
depth_ts %>% ggtsdisplay(main="")

build in more convinient way graphics for acf and pacf;

acf(depth_ts)

pacf(depth_ts)

From the graphics we can suppose that from ACF and adf test q = 16, from PACF - p=13-15. We will variants and find a model with the lowest AICc. Also we will look at residual plots and notice if lag is between threshold values of autocorrelation functions.

Predict data

Lets predict data

autoplot(forecast(arima, h=370))

We got predict for our data.If we check residuals we can see that it is white noise. So our model is really correct

Testing model

Now we should test our model. From the graphic we see that all predicted values are in confidence interval.

hold <- window(depth_ts, start = 4000)
## Warning in window.default(x, ...): 'start' value not changed
fit_no_holdout <- arima(depth_ts[-c(4000:4198)], order=c(14,1, 16))
fcast_no_holdout <- forecast(fit_no_holdout,h=770)
plot(fcast_no_holdout)
lines(depth_ts[c(4000:4198)])

Cross validation

We should use cross validation to choose parameters for our model.RMSE, MAE, MAPE will control quantity of our model (one of this funcs is enough) One of the most effective methods is sliding window method. It means that on the part of time series from t make predictions to t+n steps forward and count error. Then train our data and predict from t+n to t+2n till the end of the dataset. As a result we will get amount of n that can be put between training data and whole time series data. Or we can use Simulated Historical Forecasts, SHF from Prophet that has similar effect.

#Fit an AR(14) model to each rolling origin subset
far14 <- function(x, h){forecast(Arima(x, order=c(14,1,16)), h=h)}
e <- tsCV(lynx, far14, h=1)

#Fit the same model with a rolling window of length 30
e <- tsCV(lynx, far14, h=1, window=30)

#Example with exogenous predictors
far14_xreg <- function(x, h, xreg, newxreg) {
  forecast(Arima(x, order=c(14,1,16), xreg=xreg), xreg=newxreg)
}

y <- ts(rnorm(50))
xreg <- matrix(rnorm(100),ncol=2)
e <- tsCV(y, far14_xreg, h=3, xreg=xreg)
splitted <- ts_split(ts.obj = depth_ts, 500)
plot(splitted$train)

far2 <- function(x, h){forecast(arima, h=h)}
e <- tsCV(splitted$train, far2, h=1)
e1 <- tsCV(splitted$test, far2, h=1)
autoplot(e) + autolayer(splitted$test) + autolayer(splitted$train) + autolayer(e1)

From the picture we see that predicted data is so close to real, that even all data as in one line.
